[This case illuminates convincingly the utmost importance of vigilance and
preparedness for the early detection, identification and consequent timely
control of exotic animal diseases, especially when they appear for the first
time outside their traditional geographical boundaries. It also indicates the
importance of reference laboratories capable of applying state-of-the-art,
sophisticated diagnostic tools.
Such events have occurred before, some leading to devastating losses. South
Africa had a painful lesson in 1951, when Rift valley fever, previously
unknown there, had its 6-month-long unhindered course throughout vast areas,
infecting numerous animals and humans before being identified.
The South Africans and their British and German counterparts should be
congratulated for their achievement; others should draw the applicable
conclusions from this lesson. - Mod.AS].
